2015/11/30										
										
	--will need to change the event class--text will need to be a producer<string>
		not a string itself, since it may need to change based on the gamestate
		(e.g., refer to an NPC's name in the text).  Likewise for options text.
		-Related to this, when do should events be instantiated?  When should the 
		objects created by teh event builder be read into memory?  Does the builder
		create event objects that get written to file, or just text files that get
		used when creating the event objects?  is it feasible to keep all the events
		in memory, or do we need to keep them on disk until they're needed?
		--should the private variable for the text be just a string, but the 
			interpretter be part of the function that returns it?  So that mapping
			what G types into the actually shows up on screen is done within the
			event class method, rather than the event builder gui?  Ditto for
			all the other stuff in the Event class?  Still need to validate the
			stuff in the builder, so may make more sense to put it there...also
			probably more efficient to do any necessary mapping there?  
	--for event and option text parsing: break all input down into an arrayList of
		strings, some of which will be marked as code somehow (e.g., w/ ** on each 
		end?).  then need to have the parse be able to read the code parts.  they
		will all be generating Strings, and have a limited set of options to consider.
		Basically need flags (on gamestate and characters), and any methods attached
		to these (getName() etc).  One issue to consider is that flags may not be
		set, so need it to not crash when that is the case.  Might be a good idea
		to start with the text field as the first one w/ G?
		--note: each bit of code in the text can evaluate to a single string, so
			should be comparatively easy to parse (ie, doesn't need to be recursive
			or anything, just a look-up/get call).  
			things we might need:
			-character names
			-character gender terms (his/her/its, him/her/it, etc)
			-character flag values
			-gamestate flag values
			-for small list like this, probably best to just have a one-word 
				identifier to indicate which of these, followed by the text
				string of its name?  
					-might not work if i want to use the name of a character given
						in a flag?  or gender term of character given in a flag...
						so will need to be able to deal with compound code stuff.
				-so perhaps instead just have functions for each of these?  Or a
					single function which takes a value for all possible inputs, 
					and throws out the appropriate result from the combo?								
				-if we have a language where each command is a function that
					takes in a single parameter, and reads entirely left-to-right,
					then we just can write a recursive function that evaluates
					everything to the right of the first word, then uses that as 
					the parameter to for the function that corresponds to the first
					word.  Must be some things that take nothing as a parameter 
					(ie, the last thing on the line).  Would this gives us enough
					flexibility for the text?  Seems like so from the list above,
					but perhaps not if we add more things it needs to be able to do.
					-hisHerIts (and similar functions)
					-npcNamed (string input, character output)
					-pc (no input, returns PC)
					-valueOfCharFlag
					-valueOfStateFlag			
						-if flags contain multiple values, separated by ; then 
						we'd need functions like takeFirstValue and takeSecondValue
						etc, which seems ugly, but avoids the multiple inputs aspect.
						-alternatively, as long as we know the number of elements
						each function requires, we could have it evaluate just the
						next element, then all the rest?  	
				BUT--need to make a single lambda out of the input, not get a single
					string!  So using a bunch of functions like this won't work...
					can we build up a lambda of lambdas?  yes, can still do this.
					(l1, l2) -> {return (l3) -> (l1(l2.execute()))}
					--not sure if that syntax will work, but there is a way to do
						this with lambdas, definitely.  		
				--will want to make some test cases for this, as it's going to be
					very challenging to code up, so likely to have lots of bugs.	
	--check out scanner class--seems to do what i need for simple types...maybe can
		extend it?
	--check out prefuse string parser?
	--nashhorn javascript engine?
	https://github.com/greenjoe/lambdaFromString
			
				
